1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:10,000
Good morning.

3
00:00:10,000 --> 00:00:13,000
Today is December 14, 2015.

4
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:21,000
This is David Cline from the History Department of Virginia Tech, and also working with Southern Oral History Program at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

5
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:33,000
I'm here today on the campus of Wesley Theological Seminary with Maynard E. Moore, and I will ask you if you would just introduce yourself, and then we'll have a conversation.

6
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:47,000
All right. My name is Maynard E. Moore, and I've been in Washington for the last 35 years, so.

7
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:59,000
Great. So if we could start with just ask you a little bit about where you were born and raised, and we'll talk a little bit about your child.

8
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:16,000
Well, I was born in Petersburg, Virginia in 1938, which is fairly important as a context for me personally, because it was my.

9
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:34,000
I was raised in Petersburg, and this is a, this was a Southern town. Still is a Southern town in many important respects.

10
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:59,000
I had a long history and was the scene of a decisive battle in the Civil War, and it's where the Union troops dug a tunnel under the Confederate works, and ultimately by an accidental trigger.

11
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:09,000
They were planting dynamite and blew the Confederate works, and it's now a historic site, the crater.

12
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:23,000
And people in Petersburg never forgot that, and would place that as a prominent event in the history of the town.

13
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:40,000
It was a commercial center for decades before and after the Civil War, mainly a railhead and switching area for tobacco.

14
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:55,000
And the economy had been boosted in the early 20th century with the establishment of Fort Lee, Camp Lee → Fort Lee as a quarter master depot for the Army.

15
00:02:55,000 --> 00:03:03,000
So lots of money and people float into the area in World War II when I was growing up.

16
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:15,000
My family was Methodist. We were members of Washington Street United Methodist Church. There were 10 Methodist churches in the town.

17
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:28,000
We had a town of 35,000 people, and it was equivalent number of Baptist and other churches, so that was very much part of the life of the town.

18
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:33,000
All of which was segregated, of course.

19
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:42,000
My home church has a placard out in front of the church now on the wall.

20
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:56,000
That marks the spot that says in 1846. This was the site where the Methodist Episcopal Church, South was organized.

21
00:03:56,000 --> 00:04:07,000
And that was when the Methodist churches in the South broke over the issue of slavery from the Methodist church in the north.

22
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:12,000
And so that placard still stands to mark that occasion.

23
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:14,000
And this was your home church?

24
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:22,000
That was my home church. That's where I grew up. And where I felt the call to ministry.

25
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:39,000
And it was a member of the youth group and subsequently participated in Methodist Student Movement and the district and then was elected to state-wide office in Methodist Student Movement when I was a senior in high school.

26
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:51,000
So Maynard, in your childhood growing up in Petersburg in this particular church was the segregation of the time where racial issues talked about either at home or in the church?

27
00:04:52,000 --> 00:05:02,000
Nobody addressed racial issues probably by design unspoken.

28
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:10,000
And for the most part during those years I was asleep.

29
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:22,000
It was not an issue on my radar screen nor with my family. It was the way of life.

30
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:29,000
We lived on one of the main cross streets in town.

31
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:43,000
And the way the town was organized and as typical of most southern towns the cross streets were those that were occupied by the black population.

32
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:50,000
So we had black folks in our neighborhoods, so to speak, but not on the main streets.

33
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:57,000
And they were on the cross streets that were less cared for.

34
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:06,000
But I grew up playing with black kids until it was time to go to junior high school.

35
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:13,000
At that point my mother explained to me that they would no longer be welcome in our house.

36
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:30,000
as had previously been the case. I had always invited my black friends to come in to the house for watch a Howdy Doody show or have cookies in ice cream or you know.

37
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:38,000
I visited their houses but at the point where we went to junior high school that was no more.

38
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:47,000
No more interaction. Some of my best buddies among those black kids.
